ğŸ“– **Description:**
    The `ld` (linker) command is used to combine object files (created from source code by a compiler) into a single executable file.  Essentially, it takes multiple files that make up your program and links them together into one runnable file.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ğŸ”¹ `ld -o <filename>`   --> ğŸ“ Specifies the output executable file name.
    ğŸ”¹ `ld -l<library>`   --> ğŸ“š Links the specified library (e.g., `-lm` for the math library).
    ğŸ”¹ `ld -L<directory>`  --> ğŸ“‚ Tells `ld` where to search for libraries.
    ğŸ”¹ `ld -r`             --> ğŸ“¦ Creates a relocatable object file suitable for further linking.

ğŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ ld -o myprogram main.o function.o
    ğŸ”¹ Links two object files (`main.o` and `function.o`) and creates an executable file named `myprogram`.

    $ ld -o myprogram main.o -lm
    ğŸ”¹ Links the `main.o` object file with the math library and creates an executable file named `myprogram`.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

    $ ld -o hello hello.o
    ğŸ”¹ Creates an executable file named `hello` from the object file `hello.o`. If you get errors, you may need to link standard libraries.

